2. Which of the following functional subtypes of neurons is found in the dorsal ramus? Choose all that apply.
That's right!  Dorsal (and ventral) rami innervate skeletal muscle and skin of the body wall and limbs, and so contain somatic  motor fibres, sensory fibres and sympathetic postganglionic fibres.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Note in the accompanying figure that within the sympathetic ganglion, the preganglionic sympathetic axons synapse onto a second, multipolar, postganglionic sympathetic neuron, which gives rise to a postganglionic axon     (dotted blue line).
If the target of the sympathetic postganglionic neuron is smooth muscle or glands in the body wall or limbs, then the postganglionic axon will travel back to the spinal nerve via the grey ramus communicans. From there, sympathetics are distributed to targets in the para-axial region of the body wall via the dorsal ramus, and to targets in all other tissues of the body wall and the limbs via the ventral ramus. In the rami, they accompany the somatic motor and sensory fibres described earlier.
In Lab 2 you will learn that if the target of the postganglionic neuron is NOT the container, i.e. is not in the body wall or limbs, but is a visceral organ in, for instance, the thoracic or abdominal cavity, then the sympathetic postganglionic axon will NOT pass back to the spinal nerve via the grey ramus communicans. In this case, the sympathetic postganglionic axon will form distinct visceral nerves.
the gray ramus communicans is gray because its axon is not coated by myelin, i.e. is unmyelinated.
post = after; the postganglionic neuron comes carries information away from the sympathetic ganglion toward the target tissue
